Create a HTTPRoute:

apiVersion: gateway.networking.k8s.io/v1
kind: HTTPRoute
metadata:
  name: frontend-route
spec:
  parentRefs:
  - name: main-gateway
  rules:
  - matches:
    - path:
        type: PathPrefix
        value: /
    backendRefs:
    - name: frontend-service
      port: 80

    

🔥 Complete Flow (Your Architecture)
User → HAProxy → Gateway → HTTPRoute → Service → Pod
🧠 Step-by-step flow (what actually happens)
🔹 1. User (Browser)

User opens:

http://13.235.246.195

👉 This is your HAProxy public IP

🔹 2. HAProxy (Entry Point)

HAProxy receives request:

Frontend: listens on port 80

Then forwards to backend:

10.0.1.146:31300
10.0.1.61:31300

👉 These are Kubernetes worker nodes (NodePort)

🔹 3. NodePort (Gateway Entry)
NodeIP:31300

👉 This is mapped to:

Gateway Service (main-gateway)

✔ This is how traffic ENTERS Kubernetes

🔹 4. Gateway (kgateway)

Your Gateway:

kind: Gateway
name: main-gateway

👉 Acts like:

Layer 7 load balancer inside cluster

✔ Accepts HTTP traffic on port 80

🔹 5. HTTPRoute (Routing Logic)
kind: HTTPRoute

👉 Defines:

"Send all / traffic → frontend-service"

✔ Works like routing rules

🔹 6. Service (ClusterIP)
kind: Service
type: ClusterIP

👉 Internal load balancer:

frontend-service → selects pods

✔ No external access (internal only)

🔹 7. Pod (Your Application)
Container running your frontend (HTML app)

👉 Finally serves:

HTML
CSS
JS (your FitTrack Pro app)
🔁 Full Request Journey
1. User hits: http://13.235.246.195

2. HAProxy receives request
   ↓
3. Forwards to: 10.0.1.146:31300

4. NodePort receives request
   ↓
5. Sends to Gateway (main-gateway)

6. Gateway checks HTTPRoute
   ↓
7. HTTPRoute sends to frontend-service

8. Service forwards to Pod
   ↓
9. Pod returns HTML response

10. Response goes back same path
